<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,310,773,799]" box="[189,310,773,799]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,773,799]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,773,799]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1399,819,1022]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
The salient features of the new species include the following: frons brown, except broad transversal stripe between ocelli and narrow stripe at apex yellowish white, along near apex of median carina with several short transversal stripes, yellowish white (
<figureCitation box="[774,865,890,916]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[228,1361,823,1910]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[206,1382,812,1929]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 3. Neobelocera russa sp. nov., holotype (GUGC-FS-TN-20100801). A. Male habitus, dorsal view. B. Same, lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Same, lateral view. E. Face. F. Forewing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3817125" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3817125/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
); genae with 2–3 light brown spots (
<figureCitation box="[1293,1384,890,916]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[228,1361,823,1910]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[206,1382,812,1929]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 3. Neobelocera russa sp. nov., holotype (GUGC-FS-TN-20100801). A. Male habitus, dorsal view. B. Same, lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Same, lateral view. E. Face. F. Forewing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3817125" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3817125/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
); antennal segment I subsagittate, markedly flattened, with median longitudinal carina, the ventral apical angle longer than dorsal apical angle (
<figureCitation box="[629,721,960,986]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1895,1921]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,778,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[189,1398,770,1850]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 4. Neobelocera russa sp. nov., holotype (GUGC-FS-TN-20100801). A. Head and thorax, dorsal view. B. Face. C. Forewing. D. Male genitalia, posterior view. E. Same, lateral view. F. Aedeagus, posterior view. G. Same, lateral view. H. Genital style, posterior view. I. Same, lateral view. Scale bars: A–B, D–I = 0.2 mm; C = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3817127" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3817127/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
); ventral margin of pygofer with 3 medioventral processes short, median one slightly longer than lateral ones (
<figureCitation box="[777,871,995,1022]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1895,1921]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,778,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[189,1398,770,1850]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 4. Neobelocera russa sp. nov., holotype (GUGC-FS-TN-20100801). A. Head and thorax, dorsal view. B. Face. C. Forewing. D. Male genitalia, posterior view. E. Same, lateral view. F. Aedeagus, posterior view. G. Same, lateral view. H. Genital style, posterior view. I. Same, lateral view. Scale bars: A–B, D–I = 0.2 mm; C = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3817127" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3817127/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
); genital styles swollen subapically (
<figureCitation box="[1292,1386,995,1022]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1895,1921]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,778,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[189,1398,770,1850]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 4. Neobelocera russa sp. nov., holotype (GUGC-FS-TN-20100801). A. Head and thorax, dorsal view. B. Face. C. Forewing. D. Male genitalia, posterior view. E. Same, lateral view. F. Aedeagus, posterior view. G. Same, lateral view. H. Genital style, posterior view. I. Same, lateral view. Scale bars: A–B, D–I = 0.2 mm; C = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3817127" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3817127/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,1312,1061,1134]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,324,1061,1087]" box="[189,324,1061,1087]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1061,1087]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1061,1087]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1312,1107,1134]" box="[189,1312,1107,1134]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
The species epithet is derived from the Latin word ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yang &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2020" box="[797,861,1108,1133]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Neobelocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="russa">
<emphasis box="[797,861,1108,1133]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">russa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, referring to the body with rust color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
